responded: So line 2777 in the new code corresponds to the original line 2762, which is the `PyObject_RichCompare(vl->ob_item[i], wl->ob_item[i], op)` call. This means the recursive call is happening when comparing individual list elements.

The issue is that during this recursive comparison, one of the list objects (the parent lists, not the individual elements) gets freed, but when the recursive call returns, the original function tries to access the freed list object.

I think the issue is that I need to protect the individual items as well, not just the list objects. Let me try a different approach. Instead of trying to increment the reference count of potentially freed objects, let me store the items we need before making any recursive calls:

